  showtime56: [
    { taskNumber: 1, title: "Part 1", instruction: "You're on stage. Read the excerpt expressively, feeling the audience.", content: "From childhood we're taught that the first impression is the most important. That it shapes attitude and often determines how communication develops. There's truth in that. But there's a subtlety that's rarely mentioned. A first impression is almost always built on very limited information.", tips: ["Look forward, not at the text", "Pause after phrases", "Emphasize key words"] },
    { taskNumber: 2, title: "Part 2", instruction: "You're on stage. Read the excerpt expressively, feeling the audience.", content: "On appearance. On tone. On a few phrases someone managed to say. And that's often enough to form a conclusion that becomes very hard to change later. But beyond that first layer, there's always something more. You just have to reach it.", tips: ["Look forward, not at the text", "Pause after phrases", "Emphasize key words"] },
    { taskNumber: 3, title: "Part 3", instruction: "You're on stage. Read the excerpt expressively, feeling the audience.", content: "And that takes time - and, more importantly, willingness to reconsider your first opinion. The most valuable thing isn't the ability to make an impression. It's the ability not to get stuck in one.", tips: ["Look forward, not at the text", "Pause after phrases", "Emphasize key words"] },
  ],
